description.text:
This is Ivan Owen's design for the talon tensioner (you can find here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:232291) but I have just joined the design to the Talon base piece. I believe David Orgeman has developed an openSCAD version of this that will be more useful to people, but I thought I would upload this regardless in case someone wanted this file to test on a Tallon. David has posted the following info and should have his files uploaded soon:
I created a parametric OpenSCAD version of this, and made one with 4 tuners the size of M3 nuts. I tapped them with M3 threads and used standard button head screws as the adjusters. I tied 0.5mm braided nylon to one of the tuners with a uni knot, and put a slip knot in the other end. I set the tuner to half way in, and then started to hang weights from it. A single printed tuner was able to hold 20 pounds suspended without breaking. After the weight was removed, the tuner continued to work fine, and appeared completely undamaged. I am shocked that these are so strong. The 20 pounds far exceeds NASA figures for normal adult finger grip strength (momentary and continuous). Given that, I guess I feel no need to look further at equivalent metal parts. I will put the SCAD file out on Thingiverse in the next couple of days in case anyone else needs a custom version. Keep in mind, the strength of these will likely be at least somewhat related to the size of the tuners and the quality of the taps. You do have to be careful when you tap them that you don't split the printed layers apart.ï»¿ Thank you Ivan and David for the development of this. title: Flite Test True-X Gremlin Frame System

description.text:
This is a set of similarly sized, printable frames for the EMAX 1104 brushless motor power pack that both EMAX and Flite Test sells. It is one of the first things that I have designed in a CAD program (and the first actually good one), so let me know if there are any improvements I could make.

Files:

Top plates:
-GremlinTopPlateV3goodcamwidth.STL
-GremlinTopPlateV4.STL

Bottom plates/assemblies:
Unibody frames:
-GremlinFrame2V2sidefillets.STL (most durable, cannot use aero shell with this unless
using screws longer than 5mm)
-GremlinFrame2V3_2mm_tabs.stl (second most durable)
-GremlinFrame2V3skinnyarms.stl (least durable, less thrust lost)
-gremlinframe2V3reinforced skinny arms.stl (a bit more durable, a bit less thrust lost)

Removable arms bottom plate (the FC to motor distance is 2mm longer on this frame compared to the
unibody plates):
-Grem3 arm 2.stl (need 4 of these)
-Grem3 top plate 2.stl
-Grem3 top plate 2.stl

I just finished building the quad (with my first frame designs, as of writing this portion of the description), and on 3S, it is a lot of fun. Technically, the components from EMAX aren't rated for 3S, but I have not had any issues, and I know that many other people fly the Gremlin Power Pack on 3S with no issues as well. I would recommend using blue locktite on the motor screws, as after a couple flights (without the locktite), I had motor screws backing out. Recently, after transferring my electronics over to the main plate with skinny arms, I simply filled in the motor screw holes with hot glue after mounting the motors instead of using locktite. This has worked so far. Also, without all four motor screws in each motor, you will get a lot of vibrations. Enjoy!

Notes:

Rafts or brims are recommended so the parts stay flat and bolt together well. Supports are recommended for the aero shell and the more enclosed top plate. All other parts can be printed just fine without supports.

NOTE on vibrations: If you are having a lot of "jello"/vibrations in your video when you are on the throttle, just add more hot glue around your camera. I tried soft-mounting my motors on the first frame that I printed out, but that did nothing. Adding more hot glue, making sure that all four corners of the camera are glued, really eliminated vibrations for me.

When you are screwing the top plate down, the holes for the standoffs have some "play" in them (they are larger than the screws), so shift the top plate around and make sure that all sides of it clear the props before screwing it down before the maiden flight. For the aero shell, use some hot glue to hold the nuts in place while you screw down the shell.

You most likely will have to clean up the M3 holes. I used a small Dremel tool bit. Also, a 1/16" normal bit works well to clean out the motor mount holes on the main frame.

Upon soldering up the electronics, I realized that the ESC wires going to the FC will have to be very short or the motors will not fit over their mounting holes. Also, in order to use 10mm standoffs with the top plate, you will need to de-case your Rx and probably also remove the connector.

To hold the top plate you will need M3 10-15mm standoffs. I only have 5mm long standoff screws, and the frame is 5mm thick, so I sunk the points where the screws would be in order to accommodate for their short length.

Also, the FPV camera mount on the top plate was designed around the Lumenier Super Mini dipole all-in-one camera/vtx. I am pretty sure that a circular-polarized vtx/cam of the same size would also fit the frame.

The little T-tab between the back two arms are to zip-tie down your power lead.

To secure the aero shell to the main plate, you will need some short, hexagonal M3 standoffs or similarly sized nuts. You will probably have to clean out the holes meant for the standoffs with a Dremel tool.

My goals were to design a frame that was in a small X shape and about as small as it could be and still accommodate all of the electronics. I used Solidworks and Onshape.

description.text:
A spatial challenge and confirmed fidget toy for any age: Take a tile that has one rail and one slot and attach that tile to a set of identical tiles.

Line of Questioning:

  1. What's the minimum amount of tiles you can use to have a solid perimeter?
  2. Is there other shapes beyond a square that can be made?
  3. What if you had 8 tiles, 16, and so on?
  4. How could this be represented in an equation?

Notes:

If the tiles are scaled up it is possible to scale up the resolution as well. The tiles I printed were at 50% scale with a 0.25mm nozzle size.

The Short Story.

A student had approached me with a visual metaphor for an idea he had been working on. In my spare time, I decided to try my hand at creating the surface he was looking for and this lead to a discussion about how to attach tiles together infinitely. I only had time for Tinkercad as a design tool.

If you break this design down, you can see how it was done: https://tinkercad.com/things/9cQNf0KIxsp

Inspired by a Grade 10 student, these tiles were given one rail and one slot. The challenge was to take multiple tiles and attach them together so that the perimeter has no slots or rails showing. I printed out 8 tiles as a preliminary test and the comments coming back from the students show genuine enjoyment just playing with them.

They are much less obtuse than fidget spinners, or noisy fidget boxes, and they generate topological challenges that students can collaborate on. Yay Math!

The Fidget Tile Loop Why They Like It? I think the trick is that they slide really nicely, they're small enough that they don't take up a lot of space, and there are so many different ways you can play with them. Most importantly they have a nice heft and the surface pattern adds a tactile element.

Outcomes Based Learning Any activity with the fidget tile could
a) support resiliency and build problem-solving skills
b) the orientation of the tiles lend themselves to problems of an algorithmic nature.
c) there is the ability to plan and predict sequences of tiles that lead to interesting shapes
d) a student can discuss relationships to scaling, multiplication, and symmetry. I use them as a way of keeping the hands engaged while the mind is working on other things.

title: Zesty Nimble Effector For Ultibots K250 Delta

description.text:
Zesty Nimble E3D magnetic effector for Ultibots K250 delta printer with "Berd-Air" style cooling.

Edit: got my Nimbles and have one up and running so it is verified to work.

I designed it using the Nimble documentation.
Also note that there are some defects in the STL's generated by FreeCad but I was unable to correct them with FreeCad or Meshmixer without messing up the mesh.
They printed without any hiccups with KisSlicer generated GCode.
I used support at 88 degrees setting in KisSlicer to have support inside the E3D area but not inside the mag ball nut areas.
I have verified that after 1 hour at 250C with the silicone sock in place the E3D cooling fins were cool to the touch and no damage or softening of the PETG I printed it with was evident.
I limit my K250 to a 115mm print radius so it is untested for the complete 125mm radius.
I slightly undersized the holes for the mag balls and the cooling tube on purpose because I like to use number size bits to clean up the holes to size on my prints.
The pictures show the PTFE tubing long and not cut to length for the Nimble since I do not have one yet.
Designed to be used with the small adapter ring that comes with the Nimble.
Ball spacing is 43mm.
I kept the ball mounts in a tight radius to minimize effector tilt.
Due to the tight radius the rods (I have printed ones so no clue on the clearance of the nylon ones) barely cleared the top fan mount screws at worse case angles so I recessed them by clearance the fan as can be seen in one of the photos, although I don't think it would be absolutely necessary.
There are 2 different files for the top part "Nimble Mount" that holds the E3D V6 stationary and that the Nimble mounts to, 1 for left and 1 for right side placement of the drive cable.
The M3 nuts that the Nimble mounting screws tighten to are pressed into the top part before attaching it and once the top part is attached they are restrained from going anywhere by the effector.
You will want to press the M3 nuts in place, insert the E3D into the effector, slide the "Nimble Mount" over the E3D groove, attach the "Nimble Mount" then the Nimble goes on.
I do not know if the M3 bolts that come with the Nimble will be too long or short.
I used a couple of self threading plastic screws from some old RC servos to attach the "Nimble Mount" so I do not have a spec for them.
I used M3 nyloc nuts for the mag balls as it is extremely easy to strip the threads with standard M3 nuts. They are a tight fit and I used a smaller diameter bolt & nut to align them with the mag ball hole centerline and pressed them into the effector with a small pair of channel locks on the ball mounting surface and the aligning bolt head. Do not overtighten the mag balls, tighten with a socket held in your hand will be plenty.
I cleaned up the hole that the cooling tube goes through to a tight fit and used a piece of silicone tubing with a small zip tie to secure the cooling tube.
There is a small tower to secure the wiring to with zip ties to keep them from interfering with the rods.

description.text: I was tired of fumbling and having many close calls of dropping the engine while showing it off to friends so I designed this nice rotating display stand for this wonderful LS3 engine "ericthepoolboy" designed.

Printer Brand:

Robo 3D

Printer:

R1 ABS + PLA Model

Rafts:

No

Yes

Resolution:

.3mm

Infill:

70-90%

Notes:

I printed the stand base, engine mount retention washer, 4 motor mount spacers, and engine mount all at 90% infill and a .3mm layer height for maximum stiffness to keep from it flexing while holding the weight of the engine. The support stick will need to be printed with supports and again with a relatively high infill to keep from flexing, ( I did 90%). You will need four M4 x 30 screws to attach the engine mount to the engine, two M3 x 20-25mm screws to mount the support stick to the base, and two more m3 screws ( about 20mm or so) for the back washer that keeps the motor mount from backing out of the support stick.
To assemble, fit the support stick into the base, then using a 3/32 drill bit, drill through the 2 pre-printed holes through the base into the support stick deep enough to fit the 20-25mm m3 screws. Next, mount the engine mount to the engine with the four m4 screws while using a printed spacer on each screw (you may need to tolerance the mount screw holes to fit the m4 screws depending on your printer). Lastly, fit the hub on the motor mount through the support stick ( some sanding may be required, but you do want it slightly tight to hold the engine in a specific position as you rotate the engine around). Using that same 3/32 rill bit, retolerance the center hole on the engine mount hub for the other m3 screw, screw the back printed retention washer to it, then drill one last hole through the printed hole in the back washer into the hub and screw the last m3 screw into it. You're all set, enjoy your new beautiful display piece!

description.text:
This is derived from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:19936 by Andrew Barton.
I made one of these and thought it was a brilliant idea but I wasn't happy with the design so I made some improvements to suit my needs.
  • The lens is a push fit and needs no glue.
  • The adapter has been resized to fit over my iPhone4S case so I don't have to remove it to use the macro.
  • The top edge was thin and fragile over the flash hole. Since the flash overpowers close-up shots I never use it, so I removed the extra hole.
  • Now that the lens doesn't need glue, the hole in the upper layer is redundant. I have closed it off and added a small bump to grip the the front glass. This can be manoeuvred over the top edge of the case.
  • I made the rounded corners much smaller to overcome the nasty overhangs that distorted the first few layers.
    I am a complete OpenSCAD noob so please excuse my poor code but I decided to be brave and share it since it did use it and it did actually work!

Follow Andrew's original instructions for obtaining the lens from Surplus Shed. Delivery to the UK was only $4 which was a very pleasant surprise.
Print at a fine resolution using the Cooling options available to you. This is a small thing and will probably overheat if you don't.
Clean your lens well and hold it with the cloth as you press it, convex side first, into the hole in the adapter.
If your lens really won't fit into the hole, use OpenSCAD to increase the lens radius variable from 6.1 to 6.15 and try another print. Don't risk breaking the lens!

description.text:
Full graphics display case (Anet A6) for AM8 frame

For my own build of the AM8 frame upgrade of the Anet A8 printer i needed to alter some elements of the frame. One of those is the screen case. Ever since getting an auto level sensor and Skynet 3D installed on my printer i upgraded to an A6 screen. I hated the push buttons of the standard A8 printer.

I also wanted the case for the screen to have no visible screws on the front plate. So i modelled this case after an existing design for the A6 screen. Which attach the connecting brackets from the back. Also i wanted to include a back cover for the screen as i wanted my build to be as finished as possible.

In my build photo's of the finished product you can see i printed a version with text on the front plate. For this print i needed to use supports, but the design is made so you can print without supports if you place the front plate down in the slicer.

The files i share are therefore without text on the front plate. Off course one could edit the STL files to include text if wanted.

Also the back plate is not necessary (the screws from the brackets just pass through the backplate into the front plate) but in my opinion it completes the build to a nicer level.
(You may need to snip off the pertruding pins of the back of the screen board for the back cover to sit flush)

The brackets are labeled 1 and 2, these are the left and right brackets.

I have some horizontal spray 'risers' to irrigate a narrow strip of garden on my fence line. Variable heat from the sun has given rise to expansion and contraction of the main feeder hose lifting it from the fence railing and allowing the horizontal sprays to assume all sorts of angles. My fix was to constrain the horizontal sprays whilst allowing them some movement along the fence line. This 'clamp' does the trick.

title: Litter Robot III Open Air Fence

description.text:
After upgrading from the Litter Robot 2 to the Open Air, I loved almost all aspects of the upgrade except for the "Open Air" part.... Open Air translates into "Litter thrown everywhere".

I bought the official Open Air fence but it was worthless. I understand they didn't want to make it too big because it would lose the "Open Air" aspect... but it was wasted money.

So I decided to build something that can be attached/removed easily.

I have been using it for a month now and have had no issues with the installation (slipping, etc) and no trouble with daily usage by 2 cats. It has eliminated a lot of the litter that was thrown around while the cats are using it.

The fence was cut out of 1/8" (or 3mm) material. I tested both plywood and acrylic and both worked well. The DXF can be used for laser cutters/etc. I have included an STL of the fence also, however it's larger than most 3D printers can handle in a single print.

Printed Parts

  • 1x - Top Left Mount
  • 1x - Top Right Mount
  • 2x - Bottom Front Mount
  • 2x - Bottom Back Mount

Other parts

  • 2x - M3 x 10mm screws
  • 2x - M3 nuts

Assemble

  • Attach the bottom mounts (front and back) on both sides. Leave one side loose so it's easier to mount/align the fence on the robot.
  • Move the fence into the robot's opening and level it.
  • Make sure the bottom back mounts are gripping the opening and tighten them
  • Attach the Top left/right mounts to the robot and slide them into place to lock the fence into place.

title: Kossel Mini Flsun Magnetic Ball Joint Upgrade

description.text:
First off, let me please ask that if you like these designs and find them useful please do like, follow and share my content. And if you have any ideas or concepts to modify the content I would love to hear!

UPDATE (28/10/2017): I have added this part https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2611279 to my Thingiverse Page for those who wish to convert their roller carriage style Kossel printer to magnetic joints.

This is a magnetic ball joint upgrade for the Kossel Mini 3D printer range that use HIWIN style linear rails. The end effector is designed to use the e3d V6 style hotends as well as the various different clones that are available. This is a direct replacement to the rose/ball joint Micromake Kossel Mini sold by flsun.

The effector also allows for auto bed levelling using a limit switch and the nozzle as the means of detecting the bed surface location.

The kit can be assembled using a wide variety of parts, though has been designed around the use of 10mm magnetic ball joints.

The finishing parts for this upgrade can be purchased here http://www.chimesindustries.com/shop or the parts can be purchased from a variety of different online stores.

Print it, assemble it, try it out and let me know what you think! :) The increase in rigidity in using magnetic joints as well as linear guide rails on the Kossel printer designs really improves the print output and removes the 'slop' in the system.

I have added some images showing a possible part cooling setup for the magnetic joint setup. They can be seen here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2364103 and here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2364083 There are mounts for e3d V5 and V6 hotends (~23mm and ~25mm OD heatsink) and clone variants.

Also, if you do not have the ability to measure the length of the rods accurately to within tenths of a millimetre (0.1mm) then you may find this print helpful: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2355506 The pieces can be mounted to a piece of open beam aluminium extrusion ( e.g. one of your delta printer towers) and then each rod placed in the jig, adjusted to length and then fastened. This will ensure your rods are the same length and you do not experience any disconnects during printing and operation.

This is due to some highly stressed, constantly loaded areas from the belts and the bolts clamping the hotend clamp.
Requirements PLA and ABS can both be used, and more exotic filaments may be used as well for higher strength in the finished parts.

description.text:
This iPhone stand is designed to let you view notifications on your desk or nightstand. The front of the stand features a parabolic sound port that directs sound from the iPhone speakers to the listener. This sound port reflector preserves sound fidelity and high end frequencies. This dock also has a cutout in the back to allow the use of the USB charging cable while the phone is on display. Additionally the phone can be rotated 90-degrees in the stand for movie mode. This stand will accommodate nearly any iPhone or iPhone case. I have tested with the Commander, Otterbox, and gear case. The slot is recessed to fit a case-less iPhone as well. You can also purchase this stand from Shapeways: https://www.shapeways.com/model/1657614/ I am going to optimize it for printing cost at Shapeways and see if I can get the price down. Future Plans:
Add a cutout for rubber feet on the bottom. I just purchased some small oval shaped rubber feet to test. Make the angle adjustable. This angle is great for display purposes (like on the night stand) and watching movies but not ergonomic for tapping away on the screen. Please send me your comments and feedback if you print one. This is my first THING on THINGIVERSE and I would like to hear from you.

There are two .stl files, one with a tab at the top of the G and one without.  The tab (or circular pad) should be on your first layer and touch the build platform if using ABS plastic.  Typically this is a 2.5 hour print job and as the plastic cools the tip/top of the G will detach from the table.  The tab or pad decreases the chances of this happening.  Just cut it off with an razor knife at the end.   See the photo for how to orient it for printing.  
To print this on a Makerbot, put this on the table so that your see the G-shape from the top view, turn on supports and go.  To save time on this make your layer height .3mm.  Also, be careful when removing the supports where the phone sits or you will crack the front of the part.

Printed in black. Painted with successive layers of dry brush of grey, tope, and light grey. Cracks are painted with wider lines of the light grey and a thinner line of black.
For the ice tile, I printed in clear pla and then did a wash with a dark blue, focusing on darker lines at the square edges.
For the dirt tile, I printed in black pla, then heavily drybrushed on a darker brown. Then I added some dark grey blots that I smeared with my finger. Finally I added a little bit of green and yellow flocking and then hit the whole thing with a matte varnish.

title: Prusa i3 MkII Extruder Fan Filter Cage

description.text:
This is a filter cage that fits the 50mm x 50mm x 15mm horizontal flow fan that the Prusa i3 MkII has. I was tired of having to clean the fan blades as often as I did (I have cats - and a dusty house apparently) so I designed this cage so I could wrap some filter material around it and catch the big stuff.

After using it a month, I must say that it works well. It stops the cat hair and larger bits, but the talc type dust still goes through (this is not surprising since I am using pretty coarse 3/16" thick filter material from Amazon )but it catches a lot. There is enough foam in that sheet to make, oh like 50 foam rings for this. It'll last forever - if you don't lose it. I used some CA glue that I had laying around to fuse the ends of the foam strip together.

Anyway, I wanted to make it without using supports, and since I have a soldering iron I can dial down to 210C, I just made the two halves so that I could melt the ends of the rods to hold the two pieces together.

The holes are intentionally undersized so that I could use an X-Acto blade to carve out a little at a time so they would be press fit over the SHCS so I could just press it on and pull it off without tools. It has never come off unintentionally.

I left it hairy and dusty in the photos so you could see how well it works. That is after two weeks of printing ~8-10 hours a day.

Hey, thanks for reaching out. I totally forgot to explain what the picture shows.
The sequence shows the results after each time I ran the calibration from the video.
As a matter of fact, the first 3 cubes show "steps/mm" calibration or e-steps calibration (you should try checking this. There's a great guide on the RepRap Wiki). I will add that to the description. In my case, the extruder was pushing way less filament than the computer instructed. Something like 6mm when I needed 10mm. So very little plastic was extruded, resulting in the horizontal bands you see there, and the cubes melting.
Once the extruder pushes the right amount, I ran the calibration (the video in the description) to tune the extrusion multiplier for this particular filament. Since every material, brand and color are a little different, you should do this for every filament you get, so every one prints great.

description.text:
UPDATE 2: NEW MORE VERSATILE DESIGN https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2815021

UPDATE 1: I've updated the stl files to have a little larger chamfer at the base area. This is also an additional help for clearance.

Thumb Sticks for your XBOX ONE Controllers. One length does not work for all. I've created these to go from a 4mm raise in height all the way to 16mm. I like the 6-10mm range myself.

Been working on this design for quite a while and believe this to be a very usable Thumb Stick. The hole down the middle not only saves on material and print time but it actually really helps in the fit of your thumb. The model also includes a designed in support that should make printing easier. You just twist that out after the print is done.

The Thumb Sticks just press on your controller and has a very firm grip. I have not had one come off during gaming yet.

I've tested it, and a lot of other versions of it..., and you should have a full range of motion and can still depress the stick down at any spot. NOTE: I did have one controller that at the very top of the left stick it did seem to stop it from depressing, but when I removed the Thumb Stick and tried the controller in the same position it still wouldn't depress. So just be aware it could be the controller also.

PLEASE take the time to look at the print settings. This design does not have a lot sticking to the bed. So learn from my many hours of failures and tuning the design and the print settings.

 If you print and use one of these on your controllers and like it, Please come back   and give it a LIKE and show the MADE here also.

I printed these in PLA+ and PETG and both work really well (great layer bonding). Highly recommend you print these at a slow speed (PETG at 1500mm/min is what I used). It was designed and intended to be printed with a .4mm nozzle and with a .2mm layer thickness.

You can print these without a raft but failure rate is much higher. I've tried lots of approaches to printing this and using a raft works almost every time. I included a support with a .2mm tall grooved top and a .2mm gap from the part. I just pull it off with a needle nose pliers easily.

description.text:
360° flow fan duct for the 101superhero using E3D v6 hotend with the carrier created by workshoptinkerers (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2127629)

To prevent the fan duct touching the print base, the tip of the nozzle must be low enough from the carrier. I had created two version of the fan duct, they are 4mm and 5mm in height. If space is allowed I suggest to use 5mm one for better airflow. Change the nozzle from E3D to MK8 will also give you more 0.5mm space.

The adapter is designed for using 50mm x 50mm x 15mm fan duct but you can create your own adapter for any stronger cooling fan.

I also remixed the printhead carrier by shortening the height by 2mm and 3mm so that the nozzle can place much lower from the carrier. You need to adjust the screw for the limit switches to relevel the printhead . You may even need to change the firmware if the nozzle is too low for adjustment.

2017-05-26 - Added a semi-circle version to prevent the heat block too close to the fan duct. Also this version seems provide better cooling effect (Not 100% sure, please test it and let me know the result)

description.text:
I loved this file and it printed well with support underneath the left hand.

I did ruin the base a little getting it off the buildplate so I did a bit of my own creating and designed this quick chamfered base in Fusion 360 to make removal easier. I used Tinkercad to remove the old base and add my Fusion 360 base.

The original model can be found here: http://www.3dprintguy.co/

I have printed this model with the new chamfered base and it does indeed pop off the build plate a bit easier! I printed this on the MP select Mini V1 w/ Blue Hatchbox PLA. I think the model was about 80% to fit within the Z limit of the MP Select Mini.

I should also mention that this base is a bit larger than the original. This new updated base is 6mm thick and the original is 4mm thick.

Enjoy.

Supports are needed under the left arm, make sure your supports will touch the base plate or you could end up with a weak support pillar if it is only touching the foot!

This is a simple enclosure for a rocker switch. It's designed to hold a switch with tabs that stick out. Those tuck under the edges of the enclosure. My switch has 1mm between the tabs and the lip of the switch so that's how thick the top of the enclosure is.

I suspect that once you get the switch into this enclosure you're going to need to break the enclosure to get it back out again. It's an intentionally snug fit and while that's great for keeping the switch in place it's not fun if you want to remove it. If you're putting it together I'd recommend testing all your connections before snapping that switch into place.

There are holes on either side of the bottom to feed wire into. I didn't need a large wire gauge so the holes are only 6mm in diameter. If you need larger wire you can easily add 2mm to those holes without running into the sides of the enclosure.

Update Dec 16, 2013:
Updated the Arduino code with a new option called BLINK_TEST. The blink test is a debugging option that will blink all lights in sequence from top-left to bottom-right, column by column. Each light should activate for one second, turn off, and then the next light in the sequence should continue the pattern. This is intended to debug and ensure that all wiring is correctly assembled. If a light fails to blink, or the wrong light activates when it shouldn't, you most likely have a wiring issue with either the LED that should have been lit, or the LED that was lit out of sequence. Update May 21, 2012:
I've uploaded a Fritzing file that illustrates the schematic for the Binary Clock. Download Fritzing here http://fritzing.org/. I'm not alltogether sure how the schematic and PCB views are supposed to look, so I mainly paid attention to the breadboard view. If anyone feels inclined to update it, please send it my way! I decided that I wanted to learn how circuit boards worked, so I picked up an Arduino UNO starter kit and went to work. As my first project, I thought it would be neat to have a little home made binary clock on my desk at work, so I decided this would be my first project. The white light represents Am, yellow show the current hour, green are minutes, and red are seconds. If you are familiar with binary, you'll understand what the lights mean, otherwise check this out http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_numeral_system. Here is a small video showing it in action http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WXBh5Zqhoss&list=FLSD1-_SkYPcnzfSHYnXrqcw&feature=mh_lolz This is still a work in progress because I plan to also design a 3D printable case for it.

If you're at all interested in making this, I've included my Arduino source code. I'm going to assume, if you have an Arduino board, that you know at least the basics of how to program on it, so I'm going to leave that out. In order to wire the LED's, I'm using a method called Charlieplexing (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charlieplexing) which is using 5 digital pins to handle the function of all 19 timer lights. Each of the 5 pin wires are color coded in my pictures (8=Black, 9=Orange, 10=Green, 11=Yellow, 12=Blue) so you should be able to trace exactly how each of the 5 wires connect to each of the LED's. I have taken out all of the LED's on one of the pictures to better show the wiring (Where the LEDs are supposed to be are marked in black sharpie marks). All of the LEDs are oriented, from top to bottom, cathode then anode. If you're not familiar with this, LED's are polarized so they have to be plugged in correctly to work. Typically, cathode (negative) represents the shorter lead while anode (positive) represents the longer lead. There are also three buttons programmed into the system on pins 2, 3, and 4. These represent the "Hour", "Minute", and "Second Reset" buttons respectively. These will allow you to set the current time by incrementing the current hour or minute, or by resetting the current seconds timer back to 0. The button board also has an LED that lights up to signify whenever any of the buttons are pressed (to provide a small response that a button has been pressed). My plans for the near future are to design a 3D printable case to carry this assembly and make it look at least a little professional.

Install these between your X and Y stepper motors and the motor brackets to reduce noise and vibrations.

There are other dampers on Thingiverse, but none, that I could see, with various thicknesses. Here you'll get with the following thicknesses:

  • 0.8mm
  • 1.2mm
  • 1.6mm
  • 2.0mm
  • 2.4mm

Use the one that provides best noise reduction with no, or little, degradation in print quality.

A headphone from a 3D printer.
Download the parts, print them and, if necessary, adapt them. You should check, if they fit on your head, before you glue them. There`s enough space, for electronics or other stuff, to make your headphones smart.

promo

https://youtu.be/3FQlxuRIA_U

How to...

First, you need a speaker, that fits in the hole of the headphone case. In the original model, it is about 40mm. (1,5748 inch) Just print the parts, and solder the speakers or the electronics. Then glue the parts together. Maybe they wont fit perfectly together, so you have to edit the parts before you print them, or you could file them after printing. In the end, cover the ear piece with foam and textile.

What you need...

3D printer
Filament
Speakers
Cables
pads (to cushion your ears)
Glue or acetone
Solder
Soldering iron
